        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'> Welcome to the real world.  Man I started playing March 17th, 1999 and at that time, there were no twinks because everybody was on their first toons.  I was pretty ticked to learn that I couldn't wear patchwork armor, had to wear cloth.  When I was level 5 I got lost in the tunnels under Freeport (it was dark, I am human) and fell in some water and drowned.  Total loss.</P><P>Woke up naked and trudged on.  By at level 11 I was afraid to ding 12 because I didn't even have enough cash to buy all my level 8 spells and the level 12 ones were very, very expensive.  At level 16 I have screen caps of my groups, six necros all wearing guild robes (ie. Sr Apprentice Robes) and Derv rings, carrying cracked staffs.  Lots of cloth armor too.</P><P>At level 25 I had saved up enough cash to decide between a Staff of Writhing or a Flowing Black Robe ... and I picked the staff - go go melee necro.  At level 28 that thing starts proccing and I am a wrecking crew ... melee is very mana efficient.  Level 28 and I am finally wearing something better than my newbie robe (FBR)</P><P>Contrary to popular perception, EQ is not a game about SuperHeros.  Twinks are effectively SuperHeros, but you have to pay your dues as a regular guy first, to finance your secondaries.  And given the way the economy is now, even that is going to be difficult.</P><P>Odds are a twink you see has a sponsor, the primary ... and odds are the primary has 2500 hours played.  Mine does :p</P><P>Newbie necros (well, actually all toons) are pretty much poor their first 35 levels.  At 35, you will be pharming fine steel weapons off the Druid Defenders at the WC Druid Circle and making close to 200p and two yellow bubbles an hour, splurt from 35 to 41 in about 3 days, 3000p richer.  </P><P>Glonoin</P><P></P><P>Using your dead bodies to create a better tomorrow..</font></td>
